Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: What is another nature of Dukkha? (Answer: anxiety)
question2: How many aspects are there to Dukkha? (Answer: three)
question3: Dukkha can be translated as what word in regards to unhappiness? (Answer: unsatisfactoriness)
question4: Suffering, anxiety, unsatisfactoriness, and unease is the translation of what word? (Answer: Dukkha)
question5: How many aspects does dukkha have? (Answer: three)
question6: What does the second of the Four Noble Truths explain? (Answer: that the origin of dukkha can be known)
question7: What is the origin of dukkha? (Answer: craving (Pali: tanha) conditioned by ignorance (Pali: avijja))
question8: What is the third of the Four Noble Truths explain? (Answer: the complete cessation of dukkha is possible)
question9: What is the fourth of the Four Noble Truths explain? (Answer: identifies a path to this cessation)
question10: What is the second truth? (Answer: dukkha can be known.)

question10: To what age did Passos Coelho increase the retirement age? (Answer: 66)

question1: What sutras are reserved for those who follow the bodhisattva path? (Answer: Mahayana)
question2: What does Mahayana mean? (Answer: the Great Vehicle)
question3: What path is described as being built upon the motivation to liberate all living beings? (Answer: bodhisattva path)
question4: What sutras were transmitted in secret? (Answer: Mahayana)
question5: What sutras could have been preserved in non-human worlds? (Answer: Mahayana)
question6: What tradition says that sutras might have come from other Buddhas or Bodhisattvas? (Answer: Mahayana tradition)
question7: How many Mahayana sutras have survivied in Sanskrit or in Chinese or Tibetan translations? (Answer: six hundred)
question8: What buddhism recognizes sutras of Chinese origin? (Answer: East Asian Buddhism)
question9: When did Mahayana sutras start to influence the behavior of mainstream buddhists in India? (Answer: after the 5th century CE)
question10: What was the pejorative label for those that rejected Mahayana sutras? (Answer: Hinayana)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: What is caldeirada? (Answer: a potato-based stew that can be made from several types of fish)
question2: What meats are often used in Portuguese recipes? (Answer: beef, pork, lamb, or chicken)
question3: What are two popular Northern Portugal dishes? (Answer: arroz de sarrabulho (rice stewed in pigs blood) or the arroz de cabidela (rice and chickens meat stewed in chickens blood))
question4: What are three examples of fast food dishes in Portugal? (Answer: Francesinha (Frenchie) from Porto, and bifanas (grilled pork) or prego (grilled beef) sandwiches)
question5: Where does the Portuguese art of pastry have its origins? (Answer: in the many medieval Catholic monasteries spread widely across the country)
question6: What are the main ingredients used to make pastries in the monasteries? (Answer: almonds, flour, eggs and some liquor)
question7: What are two examples of Portuguese pastries? (Answer: pastéis de Belém (or pastéis de nata) originally from Lisbon, and ovos moles from Aveiro)
question8: Since when have Portuguese wines garnished international recognition? (Answer: since the times of the Romans)
question9: With which Roman God was Portugal associated with? (Answer: Bacchus)
question10: What are some of the best Portuguese wines? (Answer: Vinho Verde, Vinho Alvarinho, Vinho do Douro, Vinho do Alentejo, Vinho do Dão, Vinho da Bairrada and the sweet: Port Wine, Madeira Wine)

question6: What are the main ingredients used to make pastries in the monasteries? (Answer: almonds, flour, eggs and some liquor)
question7: What are two examples of Portuguese pastries? (Answer: pastéis de Belém (or pastéis de nata) originally from Lisbon, and ovos moles from Aveiro)
question8: Since when have Portuguese wines garnished international recognition? (Answer: since the times of the Romans)
question9: With which Roman God was Portugal associated with? (Answer: Bacchus)
question10: What are some of the best Portuguese wines? (Answer: Vinho Verde, Vinho Alvarinho, Vinho do Douro, Vinho do Alentejo, Vinho do Dão, Vinho da Bairrada and the sweet: Port Wine, Madeira Wine)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: The number of people targeted in a genocide should not be solely evaluated by what? (Answer: absolute terms)
question2: In addition to the numeric size of a targeted group, what other consideration was useful to the ICTY? (Answer: prominence within the group)

question4: What is the basis for suggesting that several factors regarding the activity of the perpetrators be considered?  (Answer: historical examples of genocide)
question5: The extent of what by the perpetrators was considered in an examination of their activity and level of control? (Answer: possible extent of their reach)
question6: What will always be restricted in terms of a perpetrator's intent to destroy? (Answer: the opportunity presented to him)
question7: While the factor cannot independently indicate if the targeted group is substantial, it can do what? (Answer: inform the analysis)
question8: On which date did the Genocide Convention become effective? (Answer: 12 January 1951)
question9: What was the minimum number of countries necessary to form parties?  (Answer: 20)
question10: Of the five permanent members of the UN Security Council, how many were parties to the treaty? (Answer: only two)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: Following World War II, whose bid was successful in establishing the worldwide acceptance and the nascent legal definition of genocide? (Answer: Lemkin)
question2: Which group convened officially for the first time in 1946? (Answer: United Nations General Assembly)
question3: While recognizing genocide, what did the UN General Assembly fail to do in its resolution? (Answer: provide a legal definition of the crime)
question4: Which provision was initially included in the first write-up of the Convention and then removed? (Answer: political killings)
question5: What is one of the countries that objected to the inclusion of political killings in the early version of the Convention? (Answer: USSR)
question6: What was the primary concern of other nations who objected to including political groups in the definition of genocide? (Answer: international intervention in domestic politics)
question7: Which distinguished academic of genocide highlighted several other countries opposed to including political genocide in the Convention? (Answer: William Schabas)
question8: What atrocity motivated a self-serving USSR to object to the provision of political killings drafted into the Convention? (Answer: its own Great Purge)
question9: Which group was accused by the ECHR of having an overly constricted idea of the meaning of destruction in defining genocide? (Answer: majority of legal scholars)
question10: What groups did the ECHR feel should be included as potential victims of genocide? (Answer: national, racial, religious or ethnic)

question5: What major western power is exempt from charges or claims of genocide against itself? (Answer: the United States)
question6: Along with Cyprus, what other major signatory official protested the the immunity of others from prosecution of genocide? (Answer: Norway)
question7: In 1948 the worldwide acceptance of international laws that defined and forbade genocide was promulgated by which treaty? (Answer: Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide)
question8: Perpetrators who were tried after World War II were in general found guilty of crimes against what? (Answer: humanity)
question9: An example of a more specific genocidal crime of which one could be accused was what? (Answer: crimes like murder)
question10: After WWII criminals were largely prosecuted under CPPCG for their involvement in what massive genocidal effort? (Answer: the Holocaust)

Title: Typing English Questions

question8: What is the name of the largest European aquarium? (Answer: Lisbon Oceanarium)
question9: What does the state agency Ciencia Viva promote? (Answer: scientific and technological culture among the Portuguese population)
question10: What are some examples of notable organizations focused on scientific exhibitions? (Answer: Science Museum of the University of Coimbra, the National Museum of Natural History at the University of Lisbon, and the Visionarium)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: In what form do thermal mass systems store solar energy? (Answer: heat)
question2: What is the system called that can store solar energy in the form of heat? (Answer: Thermal mass systems)
question3: What are some of the materials used in thermal storage systems? (Answer: water, earth and stone)
question4: What is something that can be accomplished by a thermal mass system? (Answer: reduce overall heating and cooling requirements)
question5: Paraffin wax is an example of what kind of storage media? (Answer: thermal)
question6: The first Glauber's salt heating system was first used where? (Answer: The "Dover House")
question7: What are some examples of phase change materials? (Answer: paraffin wax and Glauber's salt)
question8: What are the approximate temperatures that can be delivered by phase change materials? (Answer: 64 °C or 147 °F)
question9: What was the name of the heating system that first used Glauber's salt? (Answer: Dover House)
question10: Why are salts good  for thermal storage? (Answer: they are low-cost, have a high specific heat capacity and can deliver heat at temperatures compatible with conventional power systems)

question10: The oil embargo in what year was a contributing factor to the reorganization of energy policies? (Answer: 1973)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: What is the process called that can increase solar energy in areas further away from the earth's equator? (Answer: photovoltaics)
question2: Why does time have an effect of the amount of available solar energy? (Answer: during the nighttime there is little solar radiation on the surface of the Earth for solar panels to absorb)
question3: What effect does cloud coverage have on the amount of solar energy available? (Answer: clouds block incoming light from the sun and reduce the light available for solar cells)
question4: Why does land availability have an effect on solar energy? (Answer: solar panels can only be set up on land that is unowned and suitable for solar panels)
question5: Why are roofs a good place for solar panels? (Answer: many people have discovered that they can collect energy directly from their homes this way)
question6: What factors were taken into account in the estimate published in 2000 on solar energy? (Answer: insolation, cloud cover, and the land that is usable by humans)
question7: What was the total potential of solar energy found in the estimate? (Answer: 1,575–49,837 EJ per year)
question8: What is solar power? (Answer: conversion of sunlight into electricity)
question9: How is sunlight converted into electricity? (Answer: either directly using photovoltaics (PV), or indirectly using concentrated solar power (CSP))
question10: What does a concentrated solar power system use? (Answer: lenses or mirrors and tracking systems)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type

question3: Buddhism seeks to be neither pessimistic or optimistic, but what? (Answer: realistic)

question10: What was the answer given when the Buddha was asked if the body is the same as the self? (Answer: the Buddha refused to answer)

Title: Typing English Questions

question9: What does REN do? (Answer: uses sophisticated modeling to predict weather, especially wind patterns, and computer programs to calculate energy from the various renewable-energy plants)
question10: Through what renewable resource had Portugal generated electricity before the solar/wind revolution? (Answer: hydropower plants on its rivers)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: What is the definition of genocide? (Answer: a specific set of violent crimes that are committed against a certain group with the attempt to remove the entire group from existence or to destroy them)
question2: Who coined the term "genocide"? (Answer: Raphael Lemkin)
question3: Who referred to acts of genocide in 1941? (Answer: Winston Churchill)
question4: The word "genocide" was unknown until what year? (Answer: 1944)
question5: In 1941, how did Winston Churchill refer to the mass killings of Russian prisoners of war? (Answer: as "a crime without a name")
question6: What was the name of the Polish-Jewish lawyer who first described Nazi atrocities as "genocide?"  (Answer: Raphael Lemkin)
question7: What is the etymological basis of the word "genocide?" (Answer: Greek prefix geno- (meaning tribe or race) and caedere (the Latin word for to kill))
question8: As it pertains to violent crimes against targeted groups, what is the ultimate motivation within the actions of genocide? (Answer: to remove the entire group from existence or to destroy them)
question9: Several considerations were involved in meeting the requirement to determine what?   (Answer: when the targeted part is substantial enough)
question10: What is the key aspect of the targeted part of the group at the starting point of the inquiry?  (Answer: The numeric size)

question5: The ethnic cleansing perpetrated by the Serbs against Bosnia-Herzegovina was conducted with what ultimate goal in mind? (Answer: expel Muslims and Croats from their homes)
question6: Conversely the scholars who did view the Serbs' acts as constituting genocide, were backed up by what Tribunal? (Answer: the ICTY)
question7: In the 1990s, how many people were indicted for war crimes that were officially defined as genocide? (Answer: About 30)
question8: Convicted perpetrators Popovic and Beara were found guilty of genocide despite what evasive action? (Answer: several plea bargains)
question9: Tolimir was found guilty of both genocide and what other charge? (Answer: conspiracy to commit genocide)
question10: Another charge beyond the act of genocide and for which Krstic and Nikolic were found guilty was what? (Answer: aiding and abetting genocide)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: During his search for enlightenment, Gautama combined what teachings? (Answer: the yoga practice of his teacher Kalama with what later became known as "the immeasurables")
question2: What was the new kind of human invented by Gautama? (Answer: one without egotism)
question3: What are the Four Immeasurable Minds also known as? (Answer: brahmaviharas, divine abodes, or simply as four immeasurables)
question4: What is the best known of the four immeasurables? (Answer: mettā or loving-kindness meditation)
question5: The Four Immeasurables are taught as a form of meditation that cultivates what? (Answer: wholesome attitudes towards all sentient beings)
question6: Gautama combined the yoga practice of what teacher? (Answer: Kalama)
question7: Gautama invented a new kind of human without what? (Answer: egotism)
question8: What are the "four Immeasurable minds"? (Answer: love, compassion, joy, and equanimity)
question9: Who calls the four immeasurable minds "four limitless ones"? (Answer: Pema Chödrön)
question10: The Four Immeasurables are taught as a form of what? (Answer: meditation)

Title: Typing English Questions

question9: Who are some notable musical composers from Portugal? (Answer: José Vianna da Motta, Carlos Seixas, João Domingos Bomtempo, João de Sousa Carvalho, Luís de Freitas Branco and his student Joly Braga Santos)
question10: Who are some contemporary composers from Portugal? (Answer: Nuno Malo and Miguel d'Oliveira)

Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type

question3: When is empirical started? (Answer: before the doctor knows the exact identification of microorgansim)
question4: What are two examples of minor side effects caused by some antibiotics? (Answer: fever and nausea)
question5: What causes diarrhea? (Answer: disruption of the species composition in the intestinal flora)
question6: What negative effects can antibiotics have on the vaginal area? (Answer: yeast)
question7: What is one example of antibiotics that may have a possible side effect of tendon damage? (Answer: a quinolone antibiotic with a systemic corticosteroid)
question8: What is one possible serious side effect of over-using antibiotics? (Answer: alter the host microbiota)
question9: What are antibiotics screened for on mammals and humans? (Answer: negative effects)
question10: What do antibiotics need approval for? (Answer: clinical use)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: What is the process in which beings go through cycles of lifetimes as many forms of sentient life? (Answer: Rebirth)
question2: Which doctrine denies the concept of a permanent self or soul? (Answer: The doctrine of anattā (Sanskrit anātman))
question3: In Buddhism, rebirth into consecutive lives is determined by what? (Answer: the laws of cause and effect)
question4: Sentient life according to Buddhism runs between what two points? (Answer: from conception to death.)
question5: The laws of cause and effect can also be called? (Answer: karma)
question6: What is the name for the process of a succession of lifetimes? (Answer: Rebirth)
question7: What doctrine rejects the idea of permanent self? (Answer: anatta)
question8: "dependent arising" is the meaning of what word? (Answer: pratītyasamutpāda)
question9: Hinduism and Christianity use what term for a permanent self? (Answer: eternal soul)
question10: Rebirth into the Śuddhāvāsa Worlds or Pure Abodes can only be attained by who? (Answer: skilled Buddhist practitioners known as anāgāmis (non-returners))

question10: According to doctrine, because all thing don't last, attachment can lead to what? (Answer: suffering)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: What is the conclusion that one comes to when analyzing the changing physical and mental components or  person or thing? (Answer: neither the respective parts nor the person as a whole comprise a self)
question2: What is the 3rd mark of existence? (Answer: Not-self)
question3: In what form is anatta not meant as a metaphysical assertion? (Answer: Nikayas)
question4: Buddha rejected the assertion "I have a Self" and what other related assertion? (Answer: "I have no Self")
question5: What is the term for constantly changing physical and mental parts? (Answer: skandhas)
question6: What is the name of the Buddhist doctrine that states that phenomena arise together in a mutually interdependent web of cause and effect? (Answer: pratītyasamutpāda, (Sanskrit; Pali: paticcasamuppāda; Tibetan Wylie: rten cing 'brel bar 'byung ba; Chinese: 緣起))
question7: Translated into English, what does pratītyasamutpāda mean? (Answer: "dependent origination", "conditioned genesis", "dependent relationship", "dependent co-arising", "interdependent arising", or "contingency")
question8: The doctrine of pratityasumatupada is a important part of what type of metaphysics? (Answer: Buddhist)
question9: What is the most common application of the concept of pratītyasamutpāda? (Answer: the scheme of Twelve Nidānas)
question10: What does the scheme of Twelve Nidānas explain? (Answer: the continuation of the cycle of suffering and rebirth (saṃsāra) in detail.)

Title: Typing English Questions

question10: What is one of the earlier biographies on Buddhism? (Answer: the Buddhacarita)

Title: Typing English Questions

question4: What can happen if a doctor doesn't prescribe to a person's weight and prior use? (Answer: failure of medical professionals to prescribe the correct dosage)
question5: What are 3 other common forms of bad antibiotic practices? (Answer: failure to take the entire prescribed course of the antibiotic, incorrect dosage and administration, or failure to rest for sufficient recovery)

question7: What do doctors usually do when a patient seems to want antibiotics even though they may not be right? (Answer: prescribe antibiotics)

question9: Which agencies control this task force? (Answer: US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), and the National Institutes of Health (NIH))
question10: When did the French start going after overuse of antibiotics? (Answer: 2002)

Title: Typing English Questions
Description: Given an English Question, tell us what is the expected type
question1: What has been the primary focus in the study of genocide? (Answer: legal aspect of the term)
question2: In prosecuting genocide, what must the act be formally acknowledged as? (Answer: a crime)
question3: In a general aspect, what is genocide viewed as? (Answer: the deliberate killing of a certain group)
question4: In trials of genocidal crimes, what responsibly party is difficult to prosecute?  (Answer: officials in power of a state or area)
question5: Long before genocide was established as a legal term, what treaty was in place to protect various groups from persecution and mass killings? (Answer: the Peace of Westphalia)
question6: Why does genocide often go unpunished? (Answer: genocide is more often than not committed by the officials in power)
question7: Who was the Peace of Westphalia designed to protect? (Answer: ethnic, national, racial and in some instances religious groups)
question8: What year was the Peace of Westphalia signed? (Answer: 1648)
question9: When was the word "genocide" first used? (Answer: 1944)
question10: What is the etymology of the term "genocide"? (Answer: The word genocide is the combination of the Greek prefix geno- (meaning tribe or race) and caedere (the Latin word for to kill).)

Title: Typing English Questions

question10: Liberation is know as what? (Answer: nirvāṇa)

question4: When did anthropologists stop looking for cultures far away and instead began to "look across the tracks"? (Answer: only in late 1960s)

question10: What happened to Joseph I in 1758? (Answer: wounded in an attempted assassination)

question1: Between which two political ideals did Portugal bounce between? (Answer: socialism and adherence to the neoliberal model)
question2: In what year was the Portuguese Constitution approved? (Answer: 1976)
question3: For what reasons were the Portuguese Constitution rewritten? (Answer: to accommodate socialist and communist principles)
question4: What type of climate does Portugal have? (Answer: Mediterranean)
question5: In the mountainous interior north of Portugal, between what degrees is the average temperature? (Answer: 8–12 °C (46.4–53.6 °F))
question6: In the south of Portugal and on the Guadiana river basin, between what degrees does the average temperature fluctuate? (Answer: 16–19 °C (60.8–66.2 °F))
question7: How high do the mountains between Algarve and the Alentejo region reach? (Answer: 900 metres (3,000 ft))
question8: What type of climate do the archipelagos of the Azores and Madeira have? (Answer: subtropical)
question9: What makes weather predictions difficult in the archipelago region? (Answer: rough topography)
question10: What type of climate does the island of the Azores have? (Answer: Mediterranean)
